If you want to put your controller behind an API Gateway, you need to configure your application to work with the API Gateway. Here are some steps you can take to do this:

1. Configure HTTPS: You should use HTTPS for all communication between the API Gateway and your application. You can configure HTTPS in the `ConfigureWebHostDefaults` method of the `Program` class by adding the `UseHttps` method:
```csharp
public static void Main(string[] args)
{
    CreateHostBuilder(args).Build().Run();
}

public static IHostBuilder CreateHostBuilder(string[] args) =>
    Host.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
        .ConfigureWebHostDefaults(webBuilder =>
        {
            webBuilder.UseStartup<Startup>()
                .UseUrls("https://localhost:5001")
                .UseHttps();
        });
```
In this example, we're configuring the application to use HTTPS with a self-signed certificate.
2. Configure the API Gateway: You need to configure your API Gateway to forward requests to your application. This involves specifying the hostname and port of your application and the path to your controller. The exact steps for configuring the API Gateway will depend on the specific gateway you are using.
3. Configure routing: If you are using an API Gateway that modifies the path of incoming requests (e.g. by adding a prefix), you may need to configure your application to handle the modified path. You can do this by configuring routing in the `Configure` method of the `Startup` class:
```csharp
public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
{
    // ...

    app.UseRouting();

    app.UseEndpoints(endpoints =>
    {
        endpoints.MapControllerRoute(
            name: "default",
            pattern: "{controller}/{action}/{id?}");
    });
}
```
In this example, we're configuring the application to handle requests with a path that includes the name of the controller.

By default, ASP.NET Core applications listen on `localhost` and are not accessible from outside the host machine. To make your application accessible from the API Gateway, you need to listen on a publicly accessible IP address and configure your firewall to allow traffic to that address. You should also configure authentication and authorization to secure your application.

Here is an example of a complete `Program.cs` file for a .NET 6.0 web API project:
```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;

namespace YourProjectName
{
    public class Program
    {
        public static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            CreateHostBuilder(args).Build().Run();
        }

        public static IHostBuilder CreateHostBuilder(string[] args) =>
            Host.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
                .ConfigureWebHostDefaults(webBuilder =>
                {
                    webBuilder.UseStartup<Startup>();
                });
    }
}
```
This file sets up the `Main` method to create a web host builder using the `CreateDefaultBuilder` method, which loads configuration from various sources, including `appsettings.json`, environment variables, and command-line arguments. It then configures the web host to use the `Startup` class as the application's startup class.

You can customize the host builder by chaining additional methods to `CreateDefaultBuilder` or by calling `ConfigureWebHostDefaults` with a lambda expression that configures the web host. For example, you can use the `UseUrls` method to specify the URLs that the web host should listen on, or the `UseKestrel` method to configure the Kestrel web server.

To use Keycloak for authentication in your .NET 6.0 web API project, you need to perform the following steps:

1. Install the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.OpenIdConnect` package: This package provides support for OpenID Connect authentication, which is the protocol used by Keycloak. You can install this package using the following command in the Package Manager Console:
```
Install-Package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.OpenIdConnect
```
2. Configure the OpenID Connect authentication middleware: You need to configure the OpenID Connect authentication middleware to use Keycloak as the identity provider. You can do this by adding the following code to the `ConfigureServices` method of the `Startup` class:
```csharp
services.AddAuthentication(options =>
{
    options.DefaultScheme = CookieAuthenticationDefaults.AuthenticationScheme;
    options.DefaultChallengeScheme = OpenIdConnectDefaults.AuthenticationScheme;
})
.AddCookie()
.AddOpenIdConnect(options =>
{
    options.Authority = "https://your-keycloak-server/auth/realms/your-realm";
    options.ClientId = "your-client-id";
    options.ClientSecret = "your-client-secret";
    options.ResponseType = "code";
    options.Scope.Add("openid");
    options.Scope.Add("profile");
    options.SaveTokens = true;
    options.GetClaimsFromUserInfoEndpoint = true;
    options.TokenValidationParameters = new TokenValidationParameters
    {
        NameClaimType = "name",
        RoleClaimType = "role"
    };
});
```
In this example, we're configuring the authentication middleware to use a cookie-based authentication scheme as the default scheme, and to use the OpenID Connect authentication scheme as the challenge scheme. We're also configuring the OpenID Connect middleware to use Keycloak as the identity provider, and to request the `openid` and `profile` scopes. We're also specifying that the middleware should save the access and refresh tokens in the authentication properties, and that it should retrieve additional user information from the user info endpoint.
3. Enable authentication: You need to enable authentication in the `Configure` method of the `Startup` class by adding the `UseAuthentication` and `UseAuthorization` methods:
```csharp
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
```
This will cause the authentication middleware to be invoked on every request, and to set the `User` property of the `HttpContext` object to a `ClaimsPrincipal` object that represents the authenticated user.
4. Secure your API endpoints: You need to secure your API endpoints by adding the `[Authorize]` attribute to each endpoint that requires authentication:
```csharp
[Authorize]
[HttpGet]
public async Task<ActionResult<IEnumerable<User>>> GetUsers()
{
    // ...
}
```
This will cause the endpoint to return a 401 Unauthorized response if the user is not authenticated.
5. Configure Keycloak: You need to configure Keycloak to recognize your application as a valid client. This involves creating a new client in the Keycloak admin console, and configuring the client to use the appropriate redirect URIs and scopes.

To create a new client, navigate to the Keycloak admin console, select your realm, and click on the "Clients" tab. Click the "Create" button, and fill in the required information, including the client ID and secret. Make sure to set the "Valid Redirect URIs" field to the URL of your API endpoint, and to configure the "Client Scopes" and "Protocol Mappers" as necessary.

Once you have created the client, you can use the client ID and secret in the OpenID Connect middleware configuration in step 2 above.

To call the controller using React Native, you can use the `fetch()` function or a third-party library like Axios to make HTTP requests.

Here's an example using `fetch()` to get a list of users from the API:
```javascript
fetch('https://your-api-url.com/users')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    // handle the response data
    console.log(data);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    // handle any errors
    console.error(error);
  });
```
You can also include headers in the request to pass any required authentication tokens or other information. For example, to include an access token for Keycloak authentication:
```javascript
const accessToken = 'your-access-token';

fetch('https://your-api-url.com/users', {
  headers: {
    Authorization: `Bearer ${accessToken}`,
  },
})
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    // handle the response data
    console.log(data);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    // handle any errors
    console.error(error);
  });
```
Note that you will need to replace `https://your-api-url.com` with the actual URL of your API, and `your-access-token` with a valid access token for your Keycloak authentication.

